nmity with others on the other. Israel’s election, mission and vocation are played out within this tension of love, grounded in God and extending to humanity, and the opposite of love, as this finds expression in Israel’s relations with others. Israel must work out the purpose of its election and its realization in history in the tension between these two extremes. This challenge takes on great urgency in the context of advances in interfaith relations. These lead us to reflect on the meaning of Israel’s election as part of developing a contemporary Jewish theology of world religions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aJewsxElection, Doctrine of. 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh  aBiblical interpretation.  aElection.  aGentiles.  aIsrael foreign relations.  aIsrael.  aJewish identity.  aJewish state.  aJewish theology of religions.  aJudaism.  aMiddle East.  aZionism.  aagnosticism.  aantisemitism.  ablessing.  achosenness.  acontemporary Judaism.  agenocide.  ainterfaith relations.  ainterfaith theory.  ainterreligious dialogue.  alove.  anon-Jews.  aprayer.  asuffering.  atheology.  aworld religious leadership.1 aGellman, Jerome, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoshen-Gottstein, Alon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoshen-Gottstein, Alon, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGreenberg, Gershon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKallus, Menachem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKatz, Menachem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKimelman, Reuven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnohl, Israel, econtributor.4ctb4http